    <h3 id="oldLetterForms">The alphabet and its graphical representation</h3>
    <p>One of the biggest issues is how to read 16<sup>th</sup> century writing. We highlight many of the common issues below. Then if you want to, have a look at one or more of the resources available on the internet.</p>
    <p class="island island--teal">This set of tutorials is recommended by our transcribers:<br /> <a href="http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/palaeography/">The National Archives Palaeography Tutorials</a>, where palaeography means deciphering historical handwriting</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">We suggest the following are also good sources of information and examples:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="http://www.scottishhandwriting.com/">Scottish Handwriting</a> </li>
      <li><a href="http://www.amberskyline.com/treasuremaps/oldhand.html">Genealogy Handwriting</a> </li>
      <li><a href="http://paleo.anglo-norman.org/empfram.html">Old Handwriting</a> </li>
    </ul>

    <p>The following image gives an excellent rendition of some early alphabets and how people of different backgrounds wrote their text.</p>

